{"version":"1.2","person":{"datePublished":"2023-11-29","name":"Carew Reynell","nameForms":[{"lang":"en","fullText":"Carew Reynell","parts":[{"type":"http://gedcomx.org/Given","value":"Carew"},{"type":"http://gedcomx.org/Surname","value":"Reynell"}],"order":"EUROTYPIC"}],"gender":"Male","lifespan":"1125–1190","fullLifespan":"Abt 1125–1190","birthDate":"+1125","birthPlace":{"address":"Pitney, Somerset, England, United Kingdom","geo":{"latitude":51.0518,"longitude":-2.7836,"@type":"GeoCoordinates"},"@type":"Place"},"christeningDate":"+1125","christeningPlace":{"address":"Pitney, Somerset, England, United Kingdom","geo":{"latitude":51.0518,"longitude":-2.7836,"@type":"GeoCoordinates"},"@type":"Place"},"deathDate":"+1190","deathPlace":{"address":"Pitney, Somerset, England, United Kingdom","geo":{"latitude":51.0518,"longitude":-2.7836,"@type":"GeoCoordinates"},"@type":"Place"},"burialDate":"+1190","burialPlace":{"address":"Pitney, Somerset, England, United Kingdom","geo":{"latitude":51.0518,"longitude":-2.7836,"@type":"GeoCoordinates"},"@type":"Place"},"userCertifiedLifeSummary":"Australian Dictionary of Biography, Volume 11 , 1988\nLife Summary [details]\nBirth\n16 September, 1883\nMagill, Adelaide, South Australia, Australia\nMarriage: May Marion Bakewell \n11 May 1910\nDeath\n27 August, 1915 (aged 31)\nGallipoli, Turkey\n\nCause of Death\nkilled in action\n\nEducation\nSt Peter's College (Adelaide)\nOccupation\narmy officer\nwinemaker\nMilitary Service\nWorld War I\nDardanelles campaign, 1915-16\nKey Organisations\nAdelaide Hunt Club\nWorkplaces\nWalter Reynell & Sons\nCarew Reynell Captain  NOPE!  This is not your guy!\nBirth 1125 Died 1190 Immediate Family:\nSon of Walter Reynell; Walter Reynell; Emily Reynell and Emily Reynell\nHusband of May Byard; Father of Sir Richard Reynell, Sheriff of Devon\n\n[http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Reynell_(surname)]\n\nThe original holder of the custody of the Castle at Exeter was William Renal, Richard's father, although he is conveniently passed over in most narratives. (Wm. Pole, Collections Towards a Description of the County of Devon, book II, page 40.\nThe castle is actually named \"Rougemont Castle\" because of the red rock used to build it, not much of it remains.\n\nWill. Renal is most likely a Norman, a son of one of the companions of William the Conqueror. He would be of French and Danish (Viking) descent.\nThere is no connection between the Reynell family of Devon and other parts of England descended from this William and the Reynel family of Reynel, France.\n\nhttps://www.geni.com/people/Captain-Carew-Reynell/6000000003725024278\n\nCarew Reynell (1883-1915), winemaker and soldier, was born on 16 September 1883 at Magill near Adelaide, fourth child and first son of Walter Reynell and his wife Emily, née Bakewell, grandson of John Reynell and brother of Gladys Reynell. He was raised at Reynella and at 17 returned home from the Collegiate School of St Peter, Adelaide, to learn winemaking. He soon displayed a keen commitment to the family business and about 1903 became manager.\n\nFrom 1906 Reynell took a particular interest in making brandy, which did not require vineyard conversion to the new grape varieties then being introduced, and which was easily exported. By 1909 he had developed Reynella's famous 'hospital' brandy, which quickly became the leading brandy in Australia. He installed new stills and equipment, and expanded plantings. In 1913, for example, he and an assistant, Gordon Cox, planted out the Jericho vineyard at the rate of ten acres (4 ha) a day; by 1914 Reynella had about 500 acres (200 ha) under vine. Reynell also grew crops and hay, and ran horses and his grandfather's prize Shropshire flock.\n\nOn 11 May 1910 he married May Marion Byard, eldest daughter of Douglas John Byard, head of Hahndorf College. They had a daughter and a son. Reynell also involved himself in the pastimes of the gentry: above medium height, athletic, well-built and a splendid horseman, he played polo regularly, in 1907 became master of the Adelaide Hunt Club (a drag hunt), and a dedicated citizen soldier. As a boy he read avidly on the Empire's military glory, and about 1900 tried to volunteer for the South African War, but was stopped by his father as under age. In July 1908 he joined the 16th Light Horse Regiment (South Australian Mounted Rifles) as a second lieutenant, and by November 1912 was a major in the 22nd Light Horse Regiment.\n\nOn 16 December 1914 Reynell joined the Australian Imperial Force as major and second-in-command of the 9th Light Horse Regiment, and landed with it on Anzac on 21 May 1915. He was killed in action on 27 August, 1915 (aged 31)\nGallipoli, Turkey","sourceList":[{"title":"Smith Family Tree - Walter Reynell 1080","sourceType":"DEFAULT","sourceLink":"https://www.smithfamilytree.net/html/walter_reynell_1216.html","sourceUri":"397F-CGT"}],"events":[{"name":"Birth","sources":"0","year":"1125","date":"Abt 1125","place":"Pitney, Somerset, England, United Kingdom"},{"name":"Christening","sources":"0","year":"1125","date":"Abt 1125","place":"Pitney, Somerset, England, United Kingdom"},{"name":"Death of Parent","sources":"0","year":"1136","date":"1136","place":"Pitney, Somerset, England","age":"11","id":"LV6H-F5P"},{"name":"Birth of Child","sources":"0","year":"1150","date":"1150","place":"Pitney, South Somerset, Somerset, England, United Kingdom","age":"25","id":"LHFN-WGP"},{"name":"Birth of Child","sources":"0","year":"1153","date":"1153","place":"Pitney, South Somerset, Somerset, England, United Kingdom","age":"28","id":"LBVP-DR4"},{"name":"Death of Parent","sources":"0","year":"1175","date":"1175","place":"Pitney, Somerset, England","age":"50","id":"G8S8-JTN"},{"name":"Death of Spouse","sources":"0","year":"1190","date":"1190","place":"Pitney, Somerset, England, United Kingdom","age":"65","id":"GWDM-9PH"},{"name":"Death","sources":"0","year":"1190","date":"1190","place":"Pitney, Somerset, England, United Kingdom","age":"65"},{